<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-155-182  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 155 182.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  March 13 1989 v10 n11 p16(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Voice and retinal scanning; does it make a system secure?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mahnke, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>There is a major debate as to the effectiveness of biometricdevices, such as fingerprint and retinal scanners, in enhancing orensuring computer system security.andP;  Univ of Pittsburgh Prof JosephW. Eaton and 'Computers andamp; Security' editor Harold Highland offeropposing views.andP;  Eaton, who wrote 'Card Carrying Americans:Privacy, Security, and the National ID Card Debate,' contends thatbiometric devices will effectively identify the identity ofpersons trying to log on to a computer and prevent theintroduction of viruses.andP;  Highland, though, believes such deviceswill only give a false sense of security, that countermeasures areor will be possible against biometric devices, and that mostcomputer crimes are committed by authorized users.andP;  Highland alsobelieves that many viruses are innocently spread by authorizedusers, making biometric indicators useless against such problems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     BiometricsSecurityAccess ControlsUser RatingsImplementationComparisonNetworks.andO;Person:    Eaton, Joseph W. (attitudes); Highland, Harold (attitudes).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>